<h2>The Transfiguration: Glory Through Flesh</h2>

<p>If the Nativity icon shows God entering human nature, the Transfiguration icon shows what human nature looks like when God shines through it.</p>

<p>On Mount Tabor, Christ's face "shone like the sun" and His garments became "white as light." The three disciples — Peter, James, and John — fell on their faces. What they saw was not a special effect. According to Byzantine theology, they were seeing Christ's divine glory, which had been present all along, now made visible through His human body.</p>

<p>This is the key: the glory did not replace His humanity. It <em>transfigured</em> it — illuminated it from within, without destroying it. His body was still a body. His face was still a face. But they were radiant with uncreated light — the same light, the tradition teaches, that will one day fill all of creation.</p>

<p>The Transfiguration is the Incarnation made visible. It is the proof of concept for theosis. If the divine light can shine through Christ's human nature without annihilating it, then it can shine through yours. The distance between God and humanity is not a gap that must be bridged by abolishing one side or the other. It has already been bridged — in Him.</p>

<h2>What This Changes</h2>

<p>Once you understand the Incarnation the way the Byzantine tradition understands it, certain things follow:</p>

<p><strong>Matter is not the enemy.</strong> If God took on a human body — with bones, blood, breath, hunger, exhaustion — then the physical world is not something to escape. It is something to transfigure. This is why the Eastern Church uses so much physical stuff in worship: bread, wine, water, oil, incense, wood, paint, gold. These are not concessions to human weakness. They are affirmations that the material world can carry the divine.</p>

<p><strong>Icons are possible.</strong> If Christ is truly God in human flesh, then He has a face that can be painted, a body that can be depicted. The icon is not an idol — it is a consequence of the Incarnation. To say Christ cannot be depicted is to deny that He truly became human. This was the argument that won the iconoclasm debates in the eighth and ninth centuries.</p>

<p><strong>The sacraments make sense.</strong> If bread and wine can become the Body and Blood of Christ in the Divine Liturgy, it is because the Incarnation has already established the precedent: matter can be united to God without ceasing to be matter.</p>

<p><strong>Every human being has infinite dignity.</strong> The Son of God did not take on an abstraction. He took on human nature — your nature, specifically. He was hungry. He wept. He slept in boats. He felt the nails. Everything that you are, He chose to be. That choice confers on every human life a weight and a worth that no political system, no economic calculation, no philosophical argument can revoke.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Maximus the Confessor, 7th century">
  The Word of God, born once in the flesh, is always willing to be born spiritually in those who desire Him.
</Pullquote>

<p>The Incarnation is not an event that happened once, two thousand years ago, in a cave in Bethlehem. It is an ongoing reality. In every Liturgy, in every icon, in every act of genuine love, the pattern of the Incarnation repeats: God enters the world through what is small, specific, physical, and human. Not in spite of those limitations, but through them.</p>

<p>That is what you see when you look at the icon of the Nativity. That is what the choir is singing about at Christmas. That is what Chalcedon was trying to protect with its four careful negatives. The God who made the universe chose to become one of us — and in doing so, opened the door for us to become like Him.</p>

<p>That door is what this entire journey is about.</p>

